Observation Details: This solitary bird flew down to a shrinking lake where fish from a recent flood were being concentrated.  It joined hundreds of Great Egrets and commenced wading head down with its open bill in the water.  The egrets ignored it.  The bird was about the size of the egrets.  It was all white, except for the black flight feathers and tail.  It had a large, square-appearing, blackish head and a long, massive, light brown, decurved bull.  It had been wading in mud, but its legs appeared to be dark colored and its muddy feet were somewhat orange/yellow.  See attached photo.

What a bird! Continuing juvenile in the stream. First seen standing on the edge of the stream about 10 feet from the road. It was standing in the shadow of the bridge. Began preening then walked into the stream to begin feeding. Very clear water made for incredible behavioral viewing. The bill would be opened under water and it would use its feet to shuffle sediment through its beak then clamp closed when it felt something hit it. Several crayfish were consumed in this manner. The feet went far under the grasses along the stream edge, dragging out food from under it right into its bill. It would shake its feet under water somewhat like a plover but more aggressively. Sometimes the grasses were too far out and the stork would give the grass a sideways shove with its body. Super cool!

Very rare/ surprising date (3rd Monmouth County record, 2nd Sandy Hook record, and 2nd December  record for New Jersey); immatures which flew into Spermaceti Cove marsh at 7:25am and continued in the area throughout the day; many photos.   Extremely unexpected, especially considering date, and quite shocking when the first one flew in at close range in a cold, drizzled sleet! This first individual flew in at 7:25am while Dave Larsen and I were counting birds out on the Spermaceti Cove boardwalk, the bird quickly dropped into the marsh just north of the boardwalk and disappeared. After a few minutes this first individual picked back up, circled the area briefly, then dropped into a roadside drainage ditch at the edge of the marsh (just south of boardwalk entrance), this was followed almost immediately by a second bird appearing from somewhere to our north and also landing into this roadside drainage ditch. Both birds picked up again, this time disappearing in the marsh to our north, before again (roughly 15min later) flying back into the aforementioned roadside drainage ditch where they stayed till at least 4:15pm.
Flying over elevator platform, circling.

Following a listserv post announcing that a Wood Stork had appeared at the Safari Park, I went over there to look for it. It was sheltering in a small pond in an area where there is no access for the general public. When I first saw the stork, it was merely standing in the shallow water and not feeding, and soon flew to a nearby snag and perched (photo). Huge bird, white overall with black flight feathers; long, heavy-duty bill with a downward curve at the end; head and neck are rough and scaly with no feathers; long, thin legs for wading, and pink feet. Regal and prehistoric looking.

Observation Details: Bird arrived at location at approximately 0645 hrs and landed on road approximately 20 feet away, then walked in to the east roadside ditch. The bird began feeding and continued to feed (catching mostly Mud Minnows) until just after 1000 hrs when across the road and began feeding in the other ditch. Continuing from yesterday; spotted while it was circling high over the lower lagoon. Very large bird with huge wingspan; white feathers overall and black flight feathers; and a long, heavy-duty, decurved bill. While soaring above, several Turkey Vultures in the same air space moved in close enough to agitate the stork. Moments later, a couple of Ravens began harassing the Wood Stork, prompting it to perform impressively fast turns and evasive maneuvers. All of the birds kept circling together while moving north and eventually disappeared.

Found previous day by Tom Boyle and seen through the day by many observers. Here is the story from today. Upon entering the site earlier at around 6:30 AM, Dave Harrison met someone leaving who said the Wood Stork (WOST) was seen in the northwest section of the pond and then moved to the southwest section. A handful of people were at the Stork pond from at least 6:45 through 9:00 AM with no sightings of the WOST.  At approximately 9:00 AM, the WOST was seen gliding into the pond from the south. No one present saw where the WOST took off from. Later, Roger Johnson was seen at the shorebird salt pond further south. He saw the WOST fly in from a point further south. This could mean the WOST is using multiple ponds at the north end of the hook.

Entering sighting on behalf of the observer/photographer Tanya Rathbun.  Tanya has kindly given a detailed report of her sighting below.  The exact location of the sighting has been withheld and a local hotspot has been selected as the best place to look for the bird.  The attached photos have a time stamp ranging from 12:36PM to 12:52PM.  The bird has not been resighted after much looking by local birders the same afternoon (8/22/2024 from 3:45 PM - 8:15 PM) and the following morning (8/23/2024).  The Wood Stork is a first for Berkshire County, MA. Congratulations Tanya!!!  Situational details of the sighting I was washing dishes and looked out the window to check on our chicken and our bird feeders out back when I saw something white right next to my deck. When I looked closer I saw that it was a large white bird, similar to an egret.  Physical description Large white bird extremely long legs with white feathers outlined with black on both wings and the back end of the bird. The bill and face was similar to the shape of a pelican and had what appeared to be hair or short feathers on the face area.  Vocal description Did not make any noises that we heard.  Behavioral description It appeared to be very interested in slugs that were under my deck and bushes long grass areas where slugs tend to hang out. We saw things in the bill and at first I thought it might be a deformity or an injury but my son stated multiple slugs were trapped in the side of the bill as the bird continued to walk around our yard. He was not afraid of us and we were able to get fairly close to get pictures.  Habitat Manicured lawn with some longer grass along the edge of a deck and under trees and bushes in the yard.  Total length of time and number of times bird was seen and/or heard At least an hour's time we were able to track it from our yard to my father's yard and watched it fly across the street to the schoolyard.  How did you rule out similar species? I used Google lens and once identified as stork I then compared pics of egrets and storks and saw the bill was very different and the wing colors were definitely that of a stork.  Optics used to view the bird: Cell phone  Distance from the bird 5-10 feet at some points further away at other times  Lighting Partly cloudy

Found previous day by Tom Boyle and seen through the day by many observers. Here is the story from today. Upon entering the site earlier at around 6:30 AM, Dave Harrison met someone leaving who said the Wood Stork (WOST) was seen in the northwest section of the pond and then moved to the southwest section. A handful of people were at the Stork pond from at least 6:45 through 9:00 AM with no sightings of the WOST.  At approximately 9:00 AM, the WOST was seen gliding into the pond from the south. No one present saw where the WOST took off from. Later, Roger Johnson was seen at the shorebird salt pond further south. He saw the WOST fly in from a point further south. This could mean the WOST is using multiple ponds at the north end of the hook.

Continuing individual first found by Erik Collins in nearby wetland 8/01/2014.  [RQD] Description based on memory and sparse field notes taken during observation: Large, long-legged wading bird observed once in flight, briefly preening, and foraging most of the time by stirring the substrate with either foot and grasping prey (small fish or crayfish) with its bill. An adult Great Egret stayed rather close to the stork and seemed to be taking advantage of the stork's ability to flush prey with its feet; on more than one occasion, the Great Egret successfully caught a fish too (see video). In direct comparison, the stork was about the same height as the Great Egret but the stork had a much larger and thicker bill, shorter but thicker neck, bulkier body, and longer and thicker legs. Its bill was slightly decurved and tapered gradually towards a blunt tip. The bill was dull yellow in color except for the base of the bill which was blackish at the base and merged with its blackish facial skin. Its irides were dark. Its legs were dark gray, becoming brownish-yellow on the lower tarsi and feet. Except for a brownish wash on its crown, nape, and upper hindneck, and black flight feathers (best seen in flight), its plumage was dingy white. The stork was initially standing on the tip of a small peninsula 170m (measured using runningmap.com) SW of our position on the shoulder of Washington County Road 15 (Manning Trail N). After about 10 minutes and for no clear reason, it flew directly towards us and started foraging along the shoreline within 30-40m of our position. When the stork flew towards us, two Sandhill Cranes (which had been heard but not seen up to this point) flushed and flew off to the southwest. Several minutes later, an adult Bald Eagle flew across the pond and landed next to another adult Bald Eagle in a dead tree on the north end of the pond. The stork ignored the eagle, but three Great Egrets (including the one foraging right next to the stork) flushed when the eagle flew across the pond. This Wood Stork was first found and identified by Erik Collins 8/01/2014, followed by daily reports from many observers. If accepted by MOURC, this would represent a third state record. It's also the second individual to be found in Minnesota this year. Having seen the Wood Stork near Blue Earth, Faribault County, in June, I believe this is clearly a different individual based on bill color, and head and neck plumage. The Washington County bird appears to be "older" and/or more advanced in its development compared to the Faribault County bird, but its plumage and bill characteristics are still most consistent with a 2nd-year bird (storks reach full adulthood in about 4 years).  .         <iframe width="560" height="315" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/3R-EdqVCNx8?rel=0" frameborder="0"></iframe>    <iframe width="560" height="315" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/TaVI6O40Zdc?rel=0" frameborder="0"></iframe>

Observation Details: See photos for species confirmation. Bird was a patient brought to Southwest Virginia Wildlife Center of Roanoke from this location. Callers reported an "egret" that they were concerned about due to it being easy to approach and seemed weak. Brief reporting from a Conservation Officer additionally addressed concerns. Pictures sent by rescuer confirmed bird was Wood Stork and not an egret. Two staff members from the Center went to go asses the situation and possibly capture the bird due to the unusual nature of one being found here--upon arrival bird was easily approached and captured by staff, making nearly no effort to get away. Bird was extremely emaciated, critically dehydrated, and covered in ectoparasites and it was decided to be admitted to the center due to poor health. Observation Details: This was a large bird even when compared with nearby Great Egrets, which likely had a body mass less than half that of the stork.  Not only did it stand taller overall, but its shorter neck resulted in the body standing higher than those of the egrets.  Even more different than this bird’s larger size was its more massive bill and its unfeathered head and neck.  I estimated the bill to be about three times aa long as the head was wide.  Moreover, the bill tapered from a base that was both wide and deep to a blunt point at the tip along a culmen that was straight for about the basal three-quarters before curving downward.  It was also at about this point where the smooth taper from the base constricted leaving the distal quarter of the bill conspicuously slimmer.  Clearly apparent was what looked like a large plate on the forehead that extended from the base of the upper mandible to the peak of the crown, behind which the nape and sides of the head were smooth and seemingly unfeathered.  The neck from the nape down to the upper back, and from the throat down to the junction with the breast was coarsely wrinkled and having an appearance approaching that of cottage cheese.  This bird’s head was small, the crown appeared rounded, and the neck was shorter and stouter than that of an egret.  The body was rather plump, and the posture was more upright than diagonal.  I noted only a slight extension of the primaries beyond the longest tertial and wingtips that appeared to reach, if not exceed, the tip of the tail, which they obscured in its entirety.  The legs were similar in length to those of the Great Egrets, yet somewhat stouter. When seen in flight, this bird had relatively broad wings with fingered wingtips, and it flew with relatively deep wingbeats interspersed with glides on wings that were held straight outward from the body.  The bill was pointed forward, and maybe slightly downward, when the bird was in flight, and the neck was outstretched.  The short tail was clearly visible when the wings were spread, and seemingly square-tipped and relatively broad.  The legs were held directly backward when the bird was in flight and they extended well beyond the tip of the tail. This bird’s plumage patterns were entirely white and black.  The body plumage was white from the base of the neck down the back and rump, and across the scapulars, wing coverts, and tertials.  The underparts were also entirely white from the base of the neck down through the breast, belly, sides, flanks, and undertail coverts.  Contrasting sharply with the white body and wing coverts, the remiges were black from the inner secondaries out through the outer primaries, but as evident in the closed wings, the tertials were white, so only a very small portion of the longest primaries was visible.  The black on the wing also extended up to the shoulder, suggesting that the primary coverts were black, but I failed to notice this expressly when the bird was in flight.  I saw a narrow band of white along the leading edge of the underwing that may have represented a pale web on one of alula feathers.  Equally as obvious as the contrast on the wings was that between the black tail and the white rump and uppertail-coverts. The bill was dusky in color, approaching blackish basally, but blending to dark brown or purplish distally.  The creamy-yellow plate on the forehead contrasted with a black eyering that was narrower above the eye than below, and which connected with the broad band that extended across at least part of the auriculars and up over the nape.  The lower end of the black appeared to extend back from the gape under the eye.  Just behind the black on the nape, the uppermost part of the back of the neck was again yellowish in color, but the rest of the neck was a medium to dark gray.  I thought the eyes were dark brown.  The legs were a slate-gray to blackish, but the feet were sharply demarcated and clearly pink, much like the color on a Western Gull.

Observation Details: What a bird! Continuing juvenile in the stream. First seen standing on the edge of the stream about 10 feet from the road. It was standing in the shadow of the bridge. Began preening then walked into the stream to begin feeding. Very clear water made for incredible behavioral viewing. The bill would be opened under water and it would use its feet to shuffle sediment through its beak then clamp closed when it felt something hit it. Several crayfish were consumed in this manner. The feet went far under the grasses along the stream edge, dragging out food from under it right into its bill. It would shake its feet under water somewhat like a plover but more aggressively. Sometimes the grasses were too far out and the stork would give the grass a sideways shove with its body. Super cool!

Observation Details: Wow! From my vantage point, I counted at least 36 Wood Storks perching high in multiple Bald Cypress trees, and I counted 2 additional ones in flight (soaring near the colony with large wingspans, white bodies with black flight feathers, dangling/dropped legs). I was able to view the group through binoculars and could clearly see the bald greyish-black, scaly heads; the dark, thick, slightly down-curved bills; and the white football-shaped bodies with black flight feathers. Very tall birds. They sat mostly still and it was very exciting to see a colony this large (and a tad eerie with this overcast sky)! Occasionally I could hear their low, dull croaking sounds. I did not spot a nest but may need someone with more expertise on their nesting sites/range to locate. I looked for paler bills to see if any juveniles were present but did not see any. (I just learned that a group of storks is apparently called a “muster”?) Low quality iPhone photos to follow.

Juvenile continuing here since earlier today, found by Anthony Vincent/Ciancimino. Standing fairly motionless in pond at (40.6217263, -74.1898608). Massive stork with fleshy bill color, spiky head feathers, overall white plumage with black flight feathers, and gray legs with pinkish feet. Loosely with a Snowy Egret. First NYC region record, and only 3rd record for southern NY. There seem to be fewer than 15 total NY records per eBird. This sighting comes amid an unprecedented post-breeding dispersal of storks, spoonbills, and other southern waders into the Midwest and Northeast. Photos.  **Update: Sadly this stork died after ingesting a meter-long piece of foam: I’m really really sad to say that this juvenile stork tragically died after eating a meter-long piece of foam. See news story at this link: https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/rare-sighting-with-tragic-end-tropical-stork-ends-up-in-ny-dies-after-eating-litter/3228382/?fbclid=IwAR2WVDqCZeGCudiY-_Trto0L2Amn5p5ubLS9Y1jLPPDyONioBATe1J9qrG0

Fourth Michigan record. Continuing juvenile visible from the east-west portion of the wildlife drive along the south bank of the Shiawassee. Bird was feeding with Great Egrets in a grassy pool south of the road, maybe 75 yards away. Flushed once and flew briefly at the approach of a bald eagle but did not depart the pool it was in. Large white wader, about the same size as Great Egret but visibly bulkier with long thick decurved bill. White overall except with black primaries and secondaries, black legs, bill mostly dull pinkish-yellow except at base where it was mottled dark gray or black, feathered head with black/brown behind the eye, somewhat paler crown, and brownish throughout most of upper neck. Fed hunched over, scraping its bill along the mud in shallow water with bill held slightly open. Seen by probably 100+ today.  Edit 8/4: too casual with "juvenile" in original desc as a synonym for immature. Bird appears to be SY or TY, not juvenile (HY).

Photographed a group of 14 immatures on a small farm pond near the town of Clyde, a few miles northwest of Montezuma NWR. The group had been present in the area for more than a week and were first discovered coming to a tiny backyard pool where they devoured the stocked Bullheads. Presumably the Wood Storks reached New York as part of the same movement that put smaller numbers in neighboring Ontario and Pennsylvania. To the best of my knowledge no adults are involved. It is unclear whether these birds originate from Florida or from further south. Accepted by New York State Avian Records Committee (NYSARC 2001-28-A/I).

Found initially this morning around 11:15 AM by Karen & Tom Beatty at this location; not observed between 11:30 AM and 3:45 PM when Jason Schatti relocated the bird per his eBird report. Bird was observed initially right up near the roadway, though on the outside of a group of cattails/phragmites. It moved further back along the linear ditch towards the tree line. If looking for this bird, give it some time as it forages down in the ditch, which wraps all around the backside of the farmfield, and it can only be seen when it moves back up into the field. Locality: Manning Trail Wood Stork farm pond
Observation Details: Discovered here on 8/1 by Erik Collins and seen every day since, by many people. Large bulky white wading bird, only a bit longer than adjacent Great Egret but much thicker and heavier. Long thick somewhat decurved heavy stork bill, pale yellowish tan in color. Legs gray, feet and lower leg paler brownish yellow. In flight, tail, primaries and secondaries black; rest of plumage dirty white. Face dark gray and appeared unfeathered (but may have been very short feathers); nape, crown, upper neck feathered, gray brown. Eye dark. Fed by walking slowly near shore with beak partly submerged and open; slowly extended leg and shuffled foot near bill to stir up bottom, then would snap bill shut upon contact with prey. Also occasionally partly flashed one or both wings while foraging, presumably to frighten prey. I saw it catch and eat about 10 small fish (maybe 2-3 inches long). Total viewing time about 10 min. (most of the time it was out of view on the southeast shore of pond). Eventually flew to and landed in oak tree to southwest.

Ongoing vagrant, one of only a handful of NYC records and my personal second for NYS. Preening cooperatively smack dab in the middle of the path along the shores of the Snag Swamp, requiring some careful repositioning along the side trails to avoid unnecessary disturbance. Massive white wading bird with black flight feathers and a wicked weapon of a bill, pale yellowish in coloration as typical of immature birds. Bald, Skeksis-esque head, with a prominent forehead plate and dingy, water-stained feathers running up the neck. Long, dark legs with gnarled, grasping toes. Heard softly clacking its bill as it adjusted its feathers and surveyed its surroundings

Remarkable numbers today. Tally up to 91, then large (and growing) northbound kettles had to be conservatively estimated. 200 is a conservative total estimate. Very large movement today, generally upriver. About a third of birds before 815 am. Low and coming off ponds (or nearby) on each side of road. 2-3  flocks of 10-12 birds and several smaller groups. Nearly all moving north. 930 am: 2 large northbound kettles of approximately 70 birds and another 30 birds generally moving north - and growing in size as they moved north and eventually out of view. Kettling with ANHI and vultures. Several other stragglers around too. Perfect weather for northbound kettling and movement - warm with south winds at 12 mph. Quite a site.

Perched on a tree adjacent to Jameson Research Island on the lagoon, then feeding along the edge of the island, and later flew across lagoon to the far shore. Free flying, unbanded. White stork with black flight feathers. Unfeathered head and neck. Head black with a sharply demarcated tan forehead. Scaly tan neck. Thick bill decurved near tip. Mottled black, fading to red and horn color distally.

Fourth Michigan record. Continuing juvenile visible from the east-west portion of the wildlife drive along the south bank of the Shiawassee. Bird was feeding with Great Egrets in a grassy pool south of the road, maybe 75 yards away. Flushed once and flew briefly at the approach of a bald eagle but did not depart the pool it was in. Large white wader, about the same size as Great Egret but visibly bulkier with long thick decurved bill. White overall except with black primaries and secondaries, black legs, bill mostly dull pinkish-yellow except at base where it was mottled dark gray or black, feathered head with black/brown behind the eye, somewhat paler crown, and brownish throughout most of upper neck. Fed hunched over, scraping its bill along the mud in shallow water with bill held slightly open. Seen by probably 100+ today.  Edit 8/4: too casual with "juvenile" in original desc as a synonym for immature. Bird appears to be SY or TY, not juvenile (HY).

Observation Details: This bird was first detected yesterday evening by Wendy Greene at the heron colony pond.  Early this morning, at 643-702 am this immature was standing on a branch in a pine tree overlooking the west part of the heron colony pond.  Yellow bill, brownish nape, thick neck ruff, reddish brown feet, black legs, black primaries and secondaries, mostly white plumage.  At 702, an immature eagle flying by the heron nests at tree top height flushed it, the Great Egret, and a few Great Blues.  The herons flew back but the stork flew upward and out of sight over C. Bay, perhaps in the direction of the Okaloosa Holding Ponds or the Niceville Spray Fields.

Viewed from the road, but on private property. Please do not enter the fields or park in driveways. Continuing juvenile - observed from 6:58 to 7:25. Very large white bird with black primaries, secondaries, and tail with gray downy head and long neck. Black underwings were visible during a few flaps, but appears to just have a black edge of feathers when standing or feeding. Large, thick, slightly decurved bill is a soft pinky salmon color and is quite pointed at the tip. Long, thick grayish pink legs with knobby knees. This buddy was eating and eating some more -  stomping and scraping his feet in the creek bed while his head was down along the muddy, grassy edges searching for food (Crawfish? Fish? Frogs?). When it found something to eat, the food was snatched up pretty quickly, clamping down aggressively and sometimes shaking its head a bit when the prey seemed bigger. We watched it start the dinner session near the covered bridge, but it made its way past a large shrub and was about halfway between the shrub and the overpass. A loud truck passed - the startled bird left the creek bed quickly and got into the grass, but after about 30-45 seconds headed right back to the creek and continued foraging and eating.  What a treat to get a view so close!

Observation Details: Photographed a group of 14 immatures on a small farm pond near the town of Clyde, a few miles northwest of Montezuma NWR. The group had been present in the area for more than a week and were first discovered coming to a tiny backyard pool where they devoured the stocked Bullheads. Presumably the Wood Storks reached New York as part of the same movement that put smaller numbers in neighboring Ontario and Pennsylvania. To the best of my knowledge no adults are involved. It is unclear whether these birds originate from Florida or from further south. Accepted by New York State Avian Records Committee (NYSARC 2001-28-A/I).

Observation Details: Continuing. Bird was on Pleasant Ridge Road, actively feeding in the flooded lawn in front of the brick house. Two of four continuing individuals found yesterday by Nina and Warren Wolf. The group flew off, leaving the area to the north just before I arrived; I was disheartened at this but waited around. Then, after about a half hour, at 1:27, two of the Wood Storks came soaring in, circling over the reservoir before dropping down in good view. Beautiful sight! The two foraged in the water for a long while before flying once again and heading back behind some vegetation at the back of the reservoir. Only these two present while I was there, but apparently all four did return later that evening.  Lifer #342!

We watched it start the dinner session near the covered bridge, but it made its way past a large shrub and was about halfway between the shrub and the overpass. A loud truck passed - the startled bird left the creek bed quickly and got into the grass, but after about 30-45 seconds headed right back to the creek and continued foraging and eating.  What a treat to get a view so close!

Remarkable numbers today. Tally up to 91, then large (and growing) northbound kettles had to be conservatively estimated. 200 is a conservative total estimate. Very large movement today, generally upriver. About a third of birds before 815 am. Low and coming off ponds (or nearby) on each side of road. 2-3  flocks of 10-12 birds and several smaller groups. Nearly all moving north. 930 am: 2 large northbound kettles of approximately 70 birds and another 30 birds generally moving north - and growing in size as they moved north and eventually out of view. Kettling with ANHI and vultures. Several other stragglers around too. Perfect weather for northbound kettling and movement - warm with south winds at 12 mph. Quite a site.

Media notes: Continuing adult Wood Stork present since initialy found on 18 July 2020 by John Sillasen was photographed here in flight by Curtis A. Marantz on 21 July 2020 along the San Jacinto River corridor south of the Perris Valley Airport, Perris, Riverside County, California.
Observation Details: This was a large wading bird that was at least as large as a large heron, but with a generally stouter bod, and a very different look to the bill, head, and neck.  The bill was about three times as long as the head was wide, and it tapered from a base that was both wide and deep to a relatively fine point, albeit with the very tip being rounded.  The taper to the bill was even and along a straight culmen for most of its length, but with the distal 10-20% tapering more strongly and curving downward to the tip.  The head was larger than that of a heron, and with a steeper forehead that had a somewhat plate-like appearance as it extended upward form the base of the upper mandible to the center of the crown.  Moreover, because this bird held the bill pointed downward, the forehead appeared steeper and the head appeared more domed than that of a heron or even an ibis.  Not only was the head unfeathered, but the neck was heavier throughout its length, lacking the S-curve that is typical of both herons and ibis, and unfeathered with a distinctly wrinkled appearance.  The body was much stockier than that of a heron, and the posture was between diagonal and vertical, and seemingly closer to the latter, when the bird perched in the tree.  Given that this bird was perched facing our direction, I was unable to see the primary projection, yet I thought the folded wings were blunt-tipped and with the wingtips reaching to about the tip of what appeared to be a rather short, and possibly square-tipped tail.  The legs were long and relatively slim, and the feet appeared to be unremarkable in size even though I did not see them very well.  When seen in flight, this was a large bird that flew with deep wingbeats on wings that had at least somewhat rounded tips.  The head and neck were outstretched, the bill was held forward and seemingly a little downward, and the legs and feet extended straight backward and well beyond a tail that was short and inconspicuous on the flying bird. The bill was a light to medium-gray in color and showing little or no obvious pattern that I can recall.  The “plate” on the forehead that extended from the base of the upper mandible to the center of the crown was pale and seemingly cream-colored, if not yellowish-buff.  Behind the forehead was a blackish mask that extended through the eye before curving upward and backward across the rear part of the crown.  I thought the lower edge of this blackish mask extended straight backward at the level of the gape.  I believe the eyes were dark.  The nape and the entirety of the neck had a coarsely wrinkled appearance and a coloration that seemed to combine grayish and cream or light yellowish to result in an overall impression not unlike that of cottage cheese.  I think the lower part of the face was similarly colored.  Given that the head and neck were entirely unfeathered, the plumage was limited to the body, wings, and tail.  Given that the stork was facing toward us when perched in the tree, I was able to see clearly that the underparts were white and unmarked from the base of the unfeathered neck down through the undertail coverts.  I further thought that what I could see of the underside of the tail was likewise white, but I did not see this as well.  Contrasting sharply with the white underparts, what I could see of the remiges in the closed wings was black from the shoulder down along the entire leading edge of the wing.  What I could see of the wing coverts was again white, which resulted in the black in the closed wings appearing as relatively narrow stripes on either side of the body.  I never saw the back or the uppersides of the wing when this bird was perched, but when it took flight, I was confident that the back and secondary coverts were white, and as such, they contrasted sharply with the black remiges.  The legs appeared to be a medium to dark gray, but the feet contrasted conspicuously as yellowish-orange and not unlike the color of orange juice.

Observation Details: Continuing. Bird was on Pleasant Ridge Road, actively feeding in the flooded lawn in front of the brick house. On my first pass, I was looking mostly in the soybean fields and must have missed the bird. I noticed it on the return pass when I pulled up to the brick house. After seeing the bird, I stopped in the road and watched it for about 20 minutes without getting out of the car. The bird approached very close, probably to within about 25-30 feet, before crossing the road. It later crossed back into the flooded lawn before flying a short distance into the next yard over. When I last saw it, it was one the two-track dirt driveway, moving away from Pleasant Ridge Road. Apparently, residents have seen it roosting in the trees behind there.

Observation Details: Continuing rarity first reported this season by Kelly Carlin on Oct. 12. Standing in the shallow water next to a Great Egret on the north side of the African Loop lake here: 33.094951, -116.997675 and watched from about 12:45-1pm.  Shortly after walking away we saw it soaring over the lake and circling higher and farther north.  Ran back to make sure the original stork was gone, which it was.  A large, white-feathered wading bird with a gray scaly head and neck, black "headphones" and eyering, dark eye, and a large, mostly grayish, downturned bill.  In flight we could see the all white underwing coverts and all black flight feathers.

Continuing, seen in early May first time by Eric Lutomski, then again on 5/27 by Alison Davies and on 5/28 by Nancy Christensen and Dan Jehl.  Several of us arrived at 9, no Stork. At 10:39 it appeared from the south, though it may have been circling around so it may have actually come in from a different direction and was gone 45 seconds later to the north.  Large stork seen as it soared overhead quite close and then circled the lagoon several times higher up and moved on. Did not land.  All white body with black remiges, dark legs, dark neck; heavy dark bill.

Locality: Manning Trail Wood Stork farm pond
Observation Details: Discovered here on 8/1 by Erik Collins and seen every day since, by many people. Large bulky white wading bird, only a bit longer than adjacent Great Egret but much thicker and heavier. Long thick somewhat decurved heavy stork bill, pale yellowish tan in color. Legs gray, feet and lower leg paler brownish yellow. In flight, tail, primaries and secondaries black; rest of plumage dirty white. Face dark gray and appeared unfeathered (but may have been very short feathers); nape, crown, upper neck feathered, gray brown. Eye dark. Fed by walking slowly near shore with beak partly submerged and open; slowly extended leg and shuffled foot near bill to stir up bottom, then would snap bill shut upon contact with prey. Also occasionally partly flashed one or both wings while foraging, presumably to frighten prey. I saw it catch and eat about 10 small fish (maybe 2-3 inches long). Total viewing time about 10 min. (most of the time it was out of view on the southeast shore of pond). Eventually flew to and landed in oak tree to southwest.

Observation Details: What a bird! Continuing juvenile in the stream. First seen standing on the edge of the stream about 10 feet from the road. It was standing in the shadow of the bridge. Began preening then walked into the stream to begin feeding. Very clear water made for incredible behavioral viewing. The bill would be opened under water and it would use its feet to shuffle sediment through its beak then clamp closed when it felt something hit it. Several crayfish were consumed in this manner. The feet went far under the grasses along the stream edge, dragging out food from under it right into its bill. It would shake its feet under water somewhat like a plover but more aggressively. Sometimes the grasses were too far out and the stork would give the grass a sideways shove with its body. Super cool!

Locality: stakeout Wood Stork, Dennis Rd., Ludington (2021)
Observation Details: Continuing.  We arrived at 10:24, missing seeing the Wood Stork by approximately 5 minutes (according to B Klick, who had just been photographing it prior to its departure to the NE).  It flew back in from the NW at 11:41, gliding south down the road, right over our heads, landing in the road south of where the cars were parked.  It eventually worked its way to the west ditch, where it foraged and made its way north 40-50 yards to where a group of us were sitting/standing next to the ditch, getting within a few feet of the group.  This bird is not people shy (or camera shy, as can be seen in the one photo).  After leaving for a while to visit Ludington State Park, we returned just in time to watch it fly off to the NE, which according to others, seems to be its pattern.

Two of four continuing individuals found yesterday by Nina and Warren Wolf. The group flew off, leaving the area to the north just before I arrived; I was disheartened at this but waited around. Then, after about a half hour, at 1:27, two of the Wood Storks came soaring in, circling over the reservoir before dropping down in good view. Beautiful sight! The two foraged in the water for a long while before flying once again and heading back behind some vegetation at the back of the reservoir. Only these two present while I was there, but apparently all four did return later that evening.  Lifer #342!

Locality: Lake Elsinore--south levee and back basin
Observation Details: This was a large bird even when compared with nearby Great Egrets, which likely had a body mass less than half that of the stork.  Not only did it stand taller overall, but its shorter neck resulted in the body standing higher than those of the egrets.  Even more different than this bird’s larger size was its more massive bill and its unfeathered head and neck.  I estimated the bill to be about three times aa long as the head was wide.  Moreover, the bill tapered from a base that was both wide and deep to a blunt point at the tip along a culmen that was straight for about the basal three-quarters before curving downward.  It was also at about this point where the smooth taper from the base constricted leaving the distal quarter of the bill conspicuously slimmer.  Clearly apparent was what looked like a large plate on the forehead that extended from the base of the upper mandible to the peak of the crown, behind which the nape and sides of the head were smooth and seemingly unfeathered.  The neck from the nape down to the upper back, and from the throat down to the junction with the breast was coarsely wrinkled and having an appearance approaching that of cottage cheese.  This bird’s head was small, the crown appeared rounded, and the neck was shorter and stouter than that of an egret.  The body was rather plump, and the posture was more upright than diagonal.  I noted only a slight extension of the primaries beyond the longest tertial and wingtips that appeared to reach, if not exceed, the tip of the tail, which they obscured in its entirety.  The legs were similar in length to those of the Great Egrets, yet somewhat stouter. When seen in flight, this bird had relatively broad wings with fingered wingtips, and it flew with relatively deep wingbeats interspersed with glides on wings that were held straight outward from the body.  The bill was pointed forward, and maybe slightly downward, when the bird was in flight, and the neck was outstretched.  The short tail was clearly visible when the wings were spread, and seemingly square-tipped and relatively broad.  The legs were held directly backward when the bird was in flight and they extended well beyond the tip of the tail. This bird’s plumage patterns were entirely white and black.  The body plumage was white from the base of the neck down the back and rump, and across the scapulars, wing coverts, and tertials.  The underparts were also entirely white from the base of the neck down through the breast, belly, sides, flanks, and undertail coverts.  Contrasting sharply with the white body and wing coverts, the remiges were black from the inner secondaries out through the outer primaries, but as evident in the closed wings, the tertials were white, so only a very small portion of the longest primaries was visible.  The black on the wing also extended up to the shoulder, suggesting that the primary coverts were black, but I failed to notice this expressly when the bird was in flight.  I saw a narrow band of white along the leading edge of the underwing that may have represented a pale web on one of alula feathers.  Equally as obvious as the contrast on the wings was that between the black tail and the white rump and uppertail-coverts. The bill was dusky in color, approaching blackish basally, but blending to dark brown or purplish distally.  The creamy-yellow plate on the forehead contrasted with a black eyering that was narrower above the eye than below, and which connected with the broad band that extended across at least part of the auriculars and up over the nape.  The lower end of the black appeared to extend back from the gape under the eye.  Just behind the black on the nape, the uppermost part of the back of the neck was again yellowish in color, but the rest of the neck was a medium to dark gray.  I thought the eyes were dark brown.  The legs were a slate-gray to blackish, but the feet were sharply demarcated and clearly pink, much like the color on a Western Gull.

Locality: Wood Stork site, Brush Run Rd.
Observation Details: Continuing juvenile (separated from adult by pale bill and feathers on neck and head), reported to be roosting here behind the house at 29123 Brush Run Road last night. Has been in the area for two weeks but has been roosting at more than one location. Birders welcome to look this evening if it returns. Left roost this morning at about 7:17 AM, seemed to descend somewhere out of view southwest of here, probably to a nearby private pond to forage. THANK YOU!!! to the Rabers for their hospitality and to Howard Gratz and Kent Miller for relaying the report to me last night.  Incredibly the 3rd Knox Wood Stork record (that I know of!) in the last 3 weeks in what has been an unimaginable saga. The first of these records was a flock of TWENTY NINE (!!!?!) individuals dropping into a yard southwest of Mount Vernon on August 17th. An unprecedented number at this latitude. About a week after this I heard of two other sightings: one by Flack Rd. (this bird) and another report at an unknown-to-me location. This relocated bird is the first chaseable one!! (others reported late). I suspect the 2 more recent records are birds from the initial flock that have lingered around, but who knows? Other confirmed OH reports in the last month have come from Franklin, Lake, and Lorain counties.

Continuing.  Thanks to all who made this sighting possible--especially Kurt Schwarz, Stella Tea and Max Wilson.  In first two photos the stork is feeding: using his feet to kick up small fishes and prey, then opening his mouth underwater to scoop them up.  In the third you see the black-edged wing that is often hidden by his white feathers.  Forth photo he is pooping.  Fifth, he is cooling by having his bill open?  Sixth to eighth he is going from standing to sitting.  His knees turn the opposite way from ours--so his feet go out in front!  Nineth and Tenth--preening.

Sixth to eighth he is going from standing to sitting.  His knees turn the opposite way from ours--so his feet go out in front!  Nineth and Tenth--preening.

Shortly after arriving the Wood Storks flew in together and landed upstream of my location of the parking area.  After a few minutes 2 flew across the road downstream of the wetland.  About twenty minutes later one Stork flew back to the wetland and circled a few times over the wetland area portions of the park across the river before flying away.  Large body birds with black wing tips and drooped bill clearly observed.  Photos of the two that flew downstream attached.

Media notes: 8:33:34AM  Returns to Ditch.    See checklist comments.
Observation Details: Continuing.   I arrived at 631AM and started the checklist.   I drove south to north down the first hill and up the second hill.  No bird in ditch.  I turned around then drove back south parking on the south hill.   I got out of the car and was walking towards the ditches (north) and the bird flew directly over me at 641AM.  Sun not even yet up.  Bird flew and landed in pond on east side of road (just north of where the blacktop begins), left there, and by 704AM was in the ditch (east side of road) where it stayed until 834AM when it walked across the road to the ditch on the west side of Dennis Road.  At about 850AM the bird walked north up the road, turned and walked west up a private drive way out of sight.  Other birders came and left - Matthew McConnel, Mike Cook and Daniel Blatt.  The bird was not wary of birders the entire time I was there in fact approaching me and others as much as we approached it.  Watched it foraging seeming to use it legs to push mud towards his beak.  Quite interesting.    One other behavior I found very interesting that I have never seen before with any bird species and therefore worth noting.  The bird was foraging in the ditch. Twice he left the ditch and defecated on the roadside and then went right back into the ditch to continue to forage.  The first time I thought I spooked it and the bird pooped as a result, moving to the ditch to get away from me.  But it happened again.  The behavior seems deliberate.  Happened twice.   Leave ditch, poop, return to ditch and forage.  Looking around the road I saw other large spots of white defection so I believe this is a standard  behavior for this bird.  See photos of 17 second sequence.  Original file numbers 1754, 1757, 1760, 1763 beginning 8:33:17 ending 8:33:34AM, in ditch, walk out, poop, return to ditch.   Fascinating.  Had real nice chat with Phil Chu at end of the observation period.

Juvenile continuing here since earlier today, found by Anthony Vincent/Ciancimino. Standing fairly motionless in pond at (40.6217263, -74.1898608). Massive stork with fleshy bill color, spiky head feathers, overall white plumage with black flight feathers, and gray legs with pinkish feet. Loosely with a Snowy Egret. First NYC region record, and only 3rd record for southern NY. There seem to be fewer than 15 total NY records per eBird. This sighting comes amid an unprecedented post-breeding dispersal of storks, spoonbills, and other southern waders into the Midwest and Northeast. Photos.  **Update: Sadly this stork died after ingesting a meter-long piece of foam: I’m really really sad to say that this juvenile stork tragically died after eating a meter-long piece of foam. See news story at this link: https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/rare-sighting-with-tragic-end-tropical-stork-ends-up-in-ny-dies-after-eating-litter/3228382/?fbclid=IwAR2WVDqCZeGCudiY-_Trto0L2Amn5p5ubLS9Y1jLPPDyONioBATe1J9qrG0

Continuing bird. Large white bird with black wing tips and a large bill, sitting 30 feet from the road. The bird is injured and favoring its right foot. The foot looked bloody and cut up, but the stork still managed to move around. I also heard it vocalize twice, letting out a quiet nasal call. It did not seem to be disturbed by my presence at all, and only flew briefly to feed on the other side of the creek. When I left, it was virtually in the same spot about 30 feet from the road. Immature, definitely a prettier Wood Stork in comparison to adults. This was lifer 300 for me! (35.2473036, -79.1924820)

Observation Details: Seen from the South road bridge. A very large white wading bird with a bare black head. Photos to come.

**RARE**. Continuing, and such a weirdly wonderful bird to be seeing on Long Island! A huge white wader with black flight feathers, a dark bald head and upper neck, a long thick and slightly drooping dark bill, and long dark legs.  Brief sightings behind the Casa Basso Restaurant at the north end when we first arrived at 12:40, but the bird soon disappeared from view as it worked its way south along the western edge of the creek.  We scouted out other vantage points and finally were able to see the bird again from Bishop Avenue at 2:00pm thanks to an alert from Karen Goldstein, but the closest and most prolonged views were from the South Road bridge soon afterwards.  A local resident passing by told us that the stork had been around for a month (!!), but birders only started hearing about it last weekend, on May 2nd.  Looks to be a near adult, based on the lingering feathers still present on the neck.

Observation Details: Continuing individual first found by Erik Collins in nearby wetland 8/01/2014.  [RQD] Description based on memory and sparse field notes taken during observation: Large, long-legged wading bird observed once in flight, briefly preening, and foraging most of the time by stirring the substrate with either foot and grasping prey (small fish or crayfish) with its bill. An adult Great Egret stayed rather close to the stork and seemed to be taking advantage of the stork's ability to flush prey with its feet; on more than one occasion, the Great Egret successfully caught a fish too (see video). In direct comparison, the stork was about the same height as the Great Egret but the stork had a much larger and thicker bill, shorter but thicker neck, bulkier body, and longer and thicker legs. Its bill was slightly decurved and tapered gradually towards a blunt tip. The bill was dull yellow in color except for the base of the bill which was blackish at the base and merged with its blackish facial skin. Its irides were dark. Its legs were dark gray, becoming brownish-yellow on the lower tarsi and feet. Except for a brownish wash on its crown, nape, and upper hindneck, and black flight feathers (best seen in flight), its plumage was dingy white. The stork was initially standing on the tip of a small peninsula 170m (measured using runningmap.com) SW of our position on the shoulder of Washington County Road 15 (Manning Trail N). After about 10 minutes and for no clear reason, it flew directly towards us and started foraging along the shoreline within 30-40m of our position. When the stork flew towards us, two Sandhill Cranes (which had been heard but not seen up to this point) flushed and flew off to the southwest. Several minutes later, an adult Bald Eagle flew across the pond and landed next to another adult Bald Eagle in a dead tree on the north end of the pond. The stork ignored the eagle, but three Great Egrets (including the one foraging right next to the stork) flushed when the eagle flew across the pond. This Wood Stork was first found and identified by Erik Collins 8/01/2014, followed by daily reports from many observers. If accepted by MOURC, this would represent a third state record. It's also the second individual to be found in Minnesota this year. Having seen the Wood Stork near Blue Earth, Faribault County, in June, I believe this is clearly a different individual based on bill color, and head and neck plumage. The Washington County bird appears to be "older" and/or more advanced in its development compared to the Faribault County bird, but its plumage and bill characteristics are still most consistent with a 2nd-year bird (storks reach full adulthood in about 4 years).  .         <iframe width="560" height="315" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/3R-EdqVCNx8?rel=0" frameborder="0"></iframe>    <iframe width="560" height="315" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/TaVI6O40Zdc?rel=0" frameborder="0"></iframe>
